(1) The Common Business-Oriented Language (COBOL) is a high-level computer
programming language developed during 1959 created for its portability and
readability of programs as normal English instead of machine language.
COBOL is known best for processing large quantities of business data through
record and data structure methodology. For example, a record clusters hetero-
geneous data: ID, name, age, and address into a single unit. A committee of
computer manufacturers, users, and U.S. government organizations created
CODASYL (Committee on Data Systems and Languages) to establish, oversee
the language standard to ensure COBOL’s portability across dissimilar
(2) The controls prescribed are applicable to all IRS COBOL programs whether

(1) Structured programming is comprised of three logical structures:
Sequence structure: In a sequential structure, the commands are
executed in sequence. The ﬂow of the program is to complete one in-
struction and then drop down and execute the next instruction and then
the next until something terminates the sequence such as the end of a
Selection structure: In a selection structure the processing is dependent
on a condition that is being tested. In COBOL, the selection structure is
usually accomplished with an IF or an EVALUATE (the implementation of
the case structure in COBOL) or with an implied IF such as the AT END
Iteration structure (LOOP STRUCTURE): The iteration structure causes
